Explanations on global competitiveness
In November, the World Economic Forum and the Center for International Development at Harvard University published the Global Competitiveness Report (Competitiveness Report) for the year 2001.
In the 75-country study, Finland, the United States, and Canada occupy the top three places, while Nicaragua, Nigeria, and Zimbabwe are at the bottom.
(All ranking lists can be read at www.weforum.com .)
As a co-responsible head of this annual study, I am often asked what competitiveness actually means.
Is there a competition among countries, in addition to military competition, that is driven by economic factors?
Does it even make sense to say that Finland is more competitive than, for example, Germany or Italy?
In our report, competitiveness is defined precisely: namely, as the ability of a country to achieve sustainable economic growth in the medium term – that is, within a period of five years.
This definition, however, does not mean that the competitiveness of a country simultaneously says something about the lack of competitiveness of another country.
With better political strategies, all countries on earth could simultaneously achieve higher growth.
Nevertheless, it makes sense to create a list of countries in terms of their growth potential.
Each country is interested in learning whether its political strategies and public institutions can keep pace with those of other countries in terms of their ability to achieve sustainable economic growth.
In some respects, economic growth is comparable to a sporting competition, where the gains of one country or region come at the expense of another country or region.
Countries, for example, compete for internationally mobile capital.
The more a country can attract foreign direct investments, the less another country gets.
It becomes completely clear when countries apply for a specific investment project.
When Intel plans a new semiconductor factory, various countries are invited to submit their offers.
The competition for the contract is fierce and often even tax benefits, improved infrastructure, and even adjustments to the study plans at the local technical university are used as sales arguments.
This year, we determined the competitiveness (growth potential) of a country based on three broad criteria: (1) Technology, (2) public institutions, and (3) macroeconomic stability.
For each of these categories, we calculated indicators whose average values were calculated using a specific method to then create a general growth and competitiveness index.
The criterion of technology refers to the ability of a country to force the development of new developments and to use technologies that have been developed elsewhere for themselves.
Countries such as the United States, Japan, Korea, Israel, and Sweden invest heavily in research and development and thus achieve high values in the field of innovation.
Other countries such as Argentina and Brazil invest less in research and development and therefore also achieve little in terms of new products and procedures.
Innovative countries also enjoy a high standard of living due to these innovations.
In this area, the United States, Canada, and Finland occupy the first three places on the ranking list.
The criterion "public institutions" refers to the quality of administration.
Is corruption a widespread problem?
Are the courts incorruptible and impartial?
Can one trust that the government will comply with its obligations in a regular manner?
Countries with well-functioning public institutions achieve higher growth rates than countries with corrupt officials and degenerate judges.
High ethical standards foster economic performance.
In this regard, the northern European countries are world leaders, and Finland, Iceland, and Denmark are also the top performers on the ranking list.
Corruption is almost unknown in these countries.
Macroeconomic stability is defined by the absence of inflation, a balanced state budget, a realistic exchange rate of the national currency, the ability of companies and the government to obtain loans on the capital market, and high confidence that the government will fulfill its financial obligations.
As an example, Asia in the late Nineties has taught us that a macroeconomic crisis can render economic growth useless, even if the companies are internationally competitive.
The three leading countries in terms of macroeconomic stability are Singapore, Ireland, and Switzerland.
In our studies on competitiveness, we have noticed that the world economy can be divided into two categories of countries: the innovative and the non-innovative.
Only about 20 countries actively engage in the development of new technologies.
In these countries, which are among the richest in the world, a first-rate system of technological innovations is a prerequisite for continuous competitiveness.
The universities must be excellent, state laboratories should have world-class level, and government and industry should strongly invest in research and development.
A key figure for future growth in these economies is the proportion of students who attend higher schools and universities after completing compulsory education.
In the U.S. and Canada, this proportion is 80%.
For the "non-innovation-friendly" countries, technology is just as important, but most new technologies are imported from abroad and not developed in the country itself.
Some countries are good at importing new technologies, others less so.
Over the past ten or fifteen years, most technology imports have taken place as part of foreign direct investments.
American companies that invested heavily in Mexico or Taiwanese companies that invested in mainland China also brought new technologies that increased the efficiency of production in the respective economy of the target country.
Therefore, it was certainly sensible for the respective countries to strive with all their might for these foreign investments: They bring not only capital but also new technologies.
A strength and at the same time a weakness of our analysis of competitiveness is that it is medium-term oriented and does not focus on the next one to two years.
Our ranking lists are not suitable for evaluating short-term cyclical changes in an economy, but they do provide insight into the long-term prospects of the major economies.
It is therefore an irony that many of the countries that occupy the top places this year, such as the US or Singapore, are actually in a recession, while others further down the ranking list, such as China (rank 39), are not affected by the global recession.
Partially, the slowdown of the economy is connected to the terrorist attacks of September 11, but it is becoming increasingly clear that the American economy and other economies connected to it through trade and production networks were already sliding into recession before September.
However, we are of the opinion that this is a temporary cyclical downturn and that the US will regain its ability to achieve strong economic growth within the next five years.
